  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When you appoint a real estate agent in Queensland, you sign a Form 6 authority. One of the key decisions in that authority is whether you are granting an exclusive listing or an open listing. The difference sounds administrative but it has real consequences for how hard your agent works, how your property is presented to the market, and what you are likely to achieve at sale.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is an exclusive listing?</h2>
      <p>An exclusive listing, sometimes called a sole agency, gives a single agent the exclusive right to sell your property for a defined period. During that period, only that agent can earn the commission. If another agent introduces a buyer and the property sells, your appointed agent still receives the full commission. If you find a buyer yourself during the exclusive period, the agent typically still earns a commission unless the Form 6 specifically carves out private sales.</p>

      <p>Exclusive listings in Brisbane's inner east typically run for 30 to 90 days, with 60 days being the most common initial term. At the end of the exclusive period, if the property has not sold, you can choose to renew, renegotiate, or switch to another arrangement. You cannot simply cancel an exclusive listing partway through without potential liability, which is why the choice of agent matters so much at the outset.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What is an open listing?</h2>
      <p>An open listing allows multiple agents to market your property simultaneously. Commission is paid only to the agent who introduces the successful buyer. In theory, this creates competition between agents and gives your property more exposure. In practice, the outcomes for sellers are usually worse.</p>

      <p>The reason is straightforward: agents under an open listing have no guaranteed return on their investment of time, money, and effort. They know that any other agent on the list could sell the property the day before they do, leaving them with nothing. As a result, most agents invest only a fraction of the resources into an open listing that they would commit to an exclusive. Professional photography, floorplans, copywriting, targeted digital campaigns, and open home schedules all cost money and take time. Agents are far less willing to invest these resources when another agent might take the commission the following week.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Why most serious agents only take exclusive listings</h2>
      <p>Any agent who consistently delivers strong results for sellers will be reluctant to take an open listing. Their business model depends on investing substantially in each campaign: high-quality marketing, active buyer management, strategic pricing advice, and skilled negotiation at the pointy end. That investment is only viable when they have a defined period in which to earn it back.</p>

      <p>When you see a property under open listing with multiple agents, it usually signals one of two things: the property has already struggled to sell under previous exclusive listings and the seller is trying a different approach, or the seller did not want to commit to a single agent and no quality agent was willing to accept the arrangement. Neither outcome positions the property favourably in buyers' minds.</p>

      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, where buyer competition for quality homes is real but buyers are also well-informed, the perception of a property listed with multiple agencies can be damaging. Buyers notice. They ask why no single agent backed it. The inference is often that something is wrong, which suppresses offers even when the property is objectively well-priced.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The pros and cons of each approach</h2>
      <p>The honest case for an exclusive listing is that it aligns your agent's incentives with your outcome. Your agent knows that if they work hard, invest in the campaign, and generate genuine buyer competition, they will earn the result. That alignment produces better marketing, more committed buyer follow-up, and stronger negotiation on your behalf at the critical moment.</p>

      <p>The honest case for an open listing is thin for most residential properties in this market. Sellers sometimes choose it because they do not want to be locked in with one agent, or because multiple agents have told them different price estimates and they want to see who performs. But the practical result is usually lower-quality marketing from each agent, less follow-through with buyers, and a longer time on market, which itself erodes buyer confidence and pricing power.</p>

      <p>There is one scenario where an open listing can make sense: a highly sought-after property where multiple agents have deep, active buyer relationships and a specific buyer on their books who is likely to transact quickly. In that case, a short open listing period can produce an early result. But this is the exception and it typically reflects unusual market conditions rather than a strategic choice that applies broadly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What happens at the end of an exclusive period?</h2>
      <p>If your property has not sold by the end of the exclusive term, you have several options. You can renew the exclusive authority with the same agent, potentially on renegotiated terms. You can switch to a different agent on a new exclusive. You can convert to an open listing, though the strategic risks above apply. Or you can withdraw the property from the market entirely and reassess.</p>

      <p>In most cases, if a property has not sold within the first 30 to 45 days of a well-run exclusive campaign, the issue is pricing rather than agent effort. A skilled agent will tell you this directly and recommend a price adjustment rather than encouraging you to renew or switch agents. Be cautious of agents who suggest renewing without addressing the pricing question honestly.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Negotiating the exclusivity period and terms</h2>
      <p>The exclusivity period is negotiable. If you are uncertain about committing to 90 days with an agent you have not worked with before, ask for a 30 or 45-day initial term with a right to renew. Most good agents will accept this, especially if you have engaged them properly on the campaign strategy and pricing.</p>

      <p>You should also confirm what happens if you find your own buyer during the exclusive period. Some Form 6 authorities allow a private sale carve-out, others do not. Read the authority before signing and ask your agent to explain the specific clause. If you have a neighbour, friend, or family member who has already expressed genuine interest in buying the property, disclose this before signing and negotiate whether that specific buyer is excluded from the commission obligation.</p>

      <p>The standard exclusive period in Brisbane's inner east is 60 days for a private treaty or expression-of-interest campaign. Auction authorities typically run 30 days to the auction date. Both are reasonable starting points. What matters more than the period length is that you choose an agent you trust, negotiate the marketing commitment clearly upfront, and give the campaign a proper chance to work.</p>

